      <trans-unit id="11216" identifier="335c5b4161a31d6033acdf2eeddbdeb6">
        <source>Why is it important for computers to be able to detect if the data received
over the internet is the same as the data that was sent?</source>
        <target>crwdns11216:0crwdne11216:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11217" identifier="c29f7287f252595df9df354b6420abe5">
        <source>What if I sent you an email that said you could now have Monday off school,
but when you received it, there was some electrical interference and a
&lt;strong&gt;bit&lt;/strong&gt; was changed from off to on so that the word &quot;now&quot; became &quot;not&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11217:0crwdne11217:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul[2]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11218" identifier="649620658c331f48f2553aae08af4855">
        <source>What would your reaction be?</source>
        <target>crwdns11218:0crwdne11218:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul[2]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11219" identifier="b39243e71cfb4fa8a791534b2c19c3b7">
        <source>Can computers correct these sorts of mistakes automatically, and how would
they do that?</source>
        <target>crwdns11219:0crwdne11219:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11220" identifier="99b0f7b08a0fea55d9673bbf7f187851">
        <source>Potential answers could include:</source>
        <target>crwdns11220:0crwdne11220:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 3&#13;
XPath: /h3</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11221" identifier="1ff77ffc6bdded16b6e39d2fdf562ab4">
        <source>Students may come up with situations where computers won't read a disc or scan a code, but they may also confuse this kind of problem with other kinds of failures such as an error in a program or a flat battery.</source>
        <target>crwdns11221:0crwdne11221:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[10]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11222" identifier="3fdc860b098f95370f461b4b7075ae22">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/school-test-error.png&quot; alt=&quot;A school test shows every question marked correct but the overall score is 0%.&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11222:0crwdne11222:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11223" identifier="cce7d7a3546b10c939bf4d1a862f4ee2">
        <source>Adults use computers for important things like banking, writing school reports, and communicating with each other.</source>
        <target>crwdns11223:0crwdne11223:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11224" identifier="bbc138bd9e0ec049a6b0b09655b7bf79">
        <source>If the information being stored got changed without anyone knowing, you'd get the wrong balance in your account (too much or too little), the wrong grade in your report, or the wrong message in an email.</source>
        <target>crwdns11224:0crwdne11224:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11225" identifier="2165ba1104175df0fe1d9f0d3a510886">
        <source>Or worst still the website you are wanting to go to for your learning or the DVD you want to play won’t work!</source>
        <target>crwdns11225:0crwdne11225:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11226" identifier="f7b13712a6a987d1df7af0c94808ba38">
        <source>This activity will look at how computers correct this automatically.</source>
        <target>crwdns11226:0crwdne11226:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11227" identifier="4460fd52c3ef567c91cd109657e20025">
        <source>Lesson starter</source>
        <target>crwdns11227:0crwdne11227:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11228" identifier="c9d4a56e4775b784341f22a32f785806">
        <source>Teacher to class: &quot;I’ve just learnt a magic trick I want to show you&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11228:0crwdne11228:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ol/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11229" identifier="2c5fb1640b2e6c7969d8b5eb88693015">
        <source>Teacher to class: &quot;So who will be my assistant?&quot;</source>
        <target>crwdns11229:0crwdne11229:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ol/li[2]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11230" identifier="92a6c2717490a8250a3ad0c6ddc16edc">
        <source>Teacher to student: Hand the cards to the student and ask them to make a
grid of 5 by 5 cards (calling it &quot;5 rows of 5 cards might be clearer for
younger students&quot;).</source>
        <target>crwdns11230:0crwdne11230:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ol/li[3]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11231" identifier="d616c7c9e17be5e42c84f85bbd13ad38">
        <source>&quot;Don't make any patterns - try to make it as random as possible&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11231:0crwdne11231:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ol/li[3]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11232" identifier="b5218b54bf0bf6ecc7725a377c5ead69">
        <source>To speed up the setup you could have two students do this task; encourage
them to leave a small gap between the cards, and not be too fussy about
making them straight.</source>
        <target>crwdns11232:0crwdne11232:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ol/li[3]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11233" identifier="952b1422b8e8be7c39f3890199f490a6">
        <source>Point out that the cards represent bits (binary digits).</source>
        <target>crwdns11233:0crwdne11233:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ol/li[4]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11234" identifier="c59778b046de01a045c2c2182cdc0144">
        <source>If they haven't studied binary numbers, you may need to just point out that
this is the way everything is represented on computers - the cards here
could represent a file, a message, a web page or even a program.</source>
        <target>crwdns11234:0crwdne11234:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ol/li[4]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11235" identifier="3b4bb852d989e35a80b3934a3cb28b90">
        <source>Teacher to class: &quot;I’m going to make this a little bit harder by adding
another row and another column&quot;.</source>
        <target>crwdns11235:0crwdne11235:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ol/li[5]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11236" identifier="01920ab7ff36a05920ccd77246115f8c">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11236:0crwdne11236:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[13]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11237" identifier="8c9f69216270fc02f31dde3411e76fcc">
        <source>Of course, you are doing this on purpose because what you want to do is make
sure that the number of black sides showing in each row and column is an even
number.</source>
        <target>crwdns11237:0crwdne11237:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11238" identifier="bd02fa003194b1d812b73550ceb3009c">
        <source>This is always possible; if the student put an odd number of black cards in a
row, you add another black card to the row; if they put an even number in the
row, add a white card, to keep it as an even number.</source>
        <target>crwdns11238:0crwdne11238:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11239" identifier="c4c89bd1b9f47eaf7dc9082ad8d3743f">
        <source>Remember that zero is an even number.</source>
        <target>crwdns11239:0crwdne11239:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11240" identifier="1eef080fa7dfb9bf38556d7141719d55">
        <source>The extra cards are called &quot;parity bits&quot; (or parity cards), but there's no
need to introduce the terminology yet, since that reveals the &quot;magic&quot;; for the
meantime the idea is for the class to think that you are just adding even more
random cards to make the task harder.</source>
        <target>crwdns11240:0crwdne11240:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[15]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11241" identifier="66062f41ee195660233738ffafeba83e">
        <source>You should practise this several times before doing it in front of the class,
as it becomes a lot easier to make it look casual when you've done it before,
and makes the trick more mysterious.</source>
        <target>crwdns11241:0crwdne11241:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[16]</note>
      </trans-unit>
